Pakistan
--------
Date: Wed, 28 Jan 2004
From: Dr Philippe Desjeux <desjeuxp@who.int>

Background data on leishmaniasis in Baluchistan & Sind (Pakistan)
-----------------------------------------------------------------
In fact in 2003 I visited with my colleagues from Eastern Mediterranean
Regional Office (EMRO) the Larkana and Dadu foci, which are located 300 km
northeast of Karachi in Sindh Province. The Province is located between
Baluchistan on the west, and on the east it borders India and Radjasthan
State. Both are well-known endemic areas for cutaneous leishmaniasis (CL).
The disease appeared in Sindh province in 2001, and the current CL epidemic
was reported to WHO Office, Islamabad in early 2002. An assessment survey
based on a case control study was immediately carried out by WHO office in
Pakistan in February 2002. 58 villages were selected for a case control
study with stratified samples. 15 people were trained. 103 active CL cases
were diagnosed. The average prevalence in Dadu District appeared to be 6.1
percent and in Larkana 3.3 percent. However, some villages reported point
prevalences from 8-20 percent. Active lesions were found more often in
males than females, and the mean age of patients was 15.6 years in Dadu and
17.5 in Larkana. Mean number of cases per household was 1.78 in Dadu and
168 in Larkana. The high proportion of active lesions compared to scars (77
vs 95 percent) confirmed the recent introduction of the parasite in the area.
Most of patients were farmers with low socio-economic level (200 to 300 Rs
per month). They live in a rural setting, where they cultivate seasonal
crops such as wheat and rice. However, due to a severe drought during the
last 3 years, crops have been severely affected.
The following were some of the clinical factors that favor Zoonotic
Cutaneous Leishmaniasis (ZCL):
- No recidivans cases
- No family cases
- Short incubation period between the infective bite and the appearance of
lesions during the transmission season
- Short duration of lesions
- More males infected than females, and a high percentage of the lesions
located on the legs -- both factors suggesting an occupational association
(i.e. doing field work in the evening in areas close to the rodent burrows).
The rodent burrows are the perfect biotope for sandfly breeding and resting
sites, because temperature and humidity are constant, organic remnants
allow maturation of sandfly larvae, and the sandflies have the opportunity
of taking a bloodmeal on the rodents.
Conclusions:
-The epidemiology corresponded to the zoonotic form of cutaneous
leishmaniasis (ZCL), and it was confirmed through the biochemical typing
(isoenzymes)of human isolates in Montpellier, France. All isolates were _L.
major_.
Some questions remain unanswered:
- The identification of the sandfly vector(s) (_P.papatasi_ and/or _P.
salehi_),
- The identification of rodents which are animal reservoirs (_Meriones
crassus_, _M. lybicus_, _M. hurrianae_, _Tatara indica_).
- Why did the epidemic occur? Facilitating factors?
There are at least 2 possible explanations:
- Due to a severe drought in recent years, there was an increased movement
of seasonal workers and nomads from Baluchistan who facilitated the
importation of the disease to Upper Sindh. As reported by local
dermatologists, the disease appeared first in villages of Upper Sindh,
close to the mountainous belt bordering Baluchistan. The importation of the
disease into a non- immune population led to the epidemic.
- Due to the drought and the subsequent reduced harvests, rodent
populations had less food available in the field, which probably forced
them to move to the peri-domestic environment, allowing frequent
transmission to humans.
--
Dr Philippe Desjeux, Medical Officer
Disease Control, Prevention and Eradication (CDS/CPE)
TDR Leishmaniasis Research Coordinator
World Health Organization
20, Avenue Appia
CH-1211 Geneva 27, Switzerland
